Here's an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP and HTML. This example uses MySQL as the database management system, but you can adjust it according to your needs.

**Database Setup**

First, let's assume that we have a table called `users` in our MySQL database:

```sql
CREATE TABLE users (
  id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(255),
  email VARCHAR(255)
);
```

**Search Bar Code**

Create an HTML file (`search.html`) and add the following code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Users</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Search Users</h1>
    <form action="search.php" method="post">
        <input type="text" name="searchTerm" placeholder="Search...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
    <?php
        // Include search results (if any)
        if(isset($_POST['searchTerm']) && !empty($_POST['searchTerm'])) {
            $searchTerm = $_POST['searchTerm'];
            $sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE '%$searchTerm%' OR email LIKE '%$searchTerm%'";
            $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);
            if(mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
                while($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
                    echo "<p>" . $row['name'] . " (" . $row['email'] . ")</p>";
                }
            } else {
                echo "No results found";
            }
        }
    ?>
</div>

</body>
</html>
```

**Search Results Code**

Create a PHP file (`search.php`) and add the following code:

```php
<?php
// Include database connection settings
include 'config.php';

// Check if search term is submitted
if (isset($_POST['searchTerm']) && !empty($_POST['searchTerm'])) {
    $searchTerm = $_POST['searchTerm'];
    $sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE '%$searchTerm%' OR email LIKE '%$searchTerm%'";
    $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

    // Check if results were found
    if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
        while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
            echo "<p>" . $row['name'] . " (" . $row['email'] . ")</p>";
        }
    } else {
        echo "No results found";
    }

} else {
    // Display search form
    include 'search.html';
}
?>
```

**Database Connection Settings**

Create a file (`config.php`) to store your database connection settings:

```php
<?php
// Database connection settings
$servername = "localhost";
$username = "your_username";
$password = "your_password";
$dbname = "your_database";

// Create a connection
$conn = mysqli_connect($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

// Check the connection
if (!$conn) {
    die("Connection failed: " . mysqli_connect_error());
}
?>
```

**Style CSS**

Create a file (`style.css`) to add some basic styling:

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

.container {
    width: 80%;
    margin: 0 auto;
}

form {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
}

input[type="text"] {
    padding: 10px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    width: 70%;
}

button[type="submit"] {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

button[type="submit"]:hover {
    background-color: #3e8e41;
}
```

This code creates a simple search bar that searches for names and emails in the `users` table. The results are displayed below the search form.

Note that this is a basic example, and you should consider implementing security measures to prevent SQL injection attacks. You can do this by using prepared statements or parameterized queries.

